This bilinear form is symmetric. That is, for all , in , and it determines : for all in .

When the characteristic of is 2, so that 2 is not a unit, it is still possible to use a quadratic form to define a symmetric bilinear form . However, can no longer be recovered from this in the same way, since for all (and is thus alternating). Alternatively, there always exists a bilinear form (not in general either unique or symmetric) such that .

The pair consisting of a finite-dimensional vector space over and a quadratic map from to is called a quadratic space, and as defined here is the associated symmetric bilinear form of . The notion of a quadratic space is a coordinate-free version of the notion of quadratic form. Sometimes, is also called a quadratic form.

Two -dimensional quadratic spaces and are isometric if there exists an invertible linear transformation (isometry) such that
